<DOC><DOCNO> AP890211-0063 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0856EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Students     02-11 0204</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea-Students,0213</SECOND><HEAD>Radical Students Clash With Police</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 500 students demanding therelease of political detainees threw rocks at riot police indowntown Seoul today and tried to march to a government prosecutor'soffice.   Police tossed about a dozen tear-gas grenades and dispersed thedemonstrators in about 40 minutes. One dissident said at least 27people were arrested.   After a two-hour rally at Myongdong Cathedral, protestersshouting ``release prisoners'' and ``arrest Chun Doo-hwan'' clashedwith riot police on a narrow shopping street.   Chun, a former South Korean president, has been sharplycriticized recently for purported abuses of power during hisseven-year adminstration.   The demonstrators also demanded that the government ``tell thetruth'' about the 1980 uprising in Kwangju.   The government says 200 students were killed and at least 1,000injured in the revolt, but critics say the numbers are much higherand have demanded another investigation.   Dozens of people were pushed and kicked as lines of studentstried unsuccessfully to ram their way past police, who repelled theprotesters with tear-gas grenades.   Unlike most recent anti-government demonstrations, the protestersdid not use firebombs.   On Friday, the government proposed legislation that would outlawthe use or manufacture of firebombs.</TEXT></DOC>